Here's how to implement all three requirements:

## 1. Custom "Cancel" back button on `EditProductPage`

```xml
<!-- EditProductPage.xaml -->
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

The `Command` binding means tapping "Cancel" runs your ViewModel logic instead of the default pop, giving you a chance to show the dialog.

```csharp
// EditProductViewModel.cs
[RelayCommand]
private async Task Back()
{
    if (HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard) return;   // user chose Stay — do nothing
    }

    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

## 2. Guard the system back gesture / hardware back button

The custom button above only covers taps on "Cancel". The user can still swipe back or press the Android hardware back button. Guard that in `AppShell`:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    // Only intercept pops (back navigation)
    if (args.Source != ShellNavigationSource.Pop)
        return;

    // Check if the current page is EditProductPage
    if (Shell.Current.CurrentPage is not Views.EditProductPage page)
        return;

    // Check for unsaved changes via the ViewModel
    if (page.BindingContext is ViewModels.EditProductViewModel vm
        && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`BackButtonBehavior.Command`** — replaces the default back button with "Cancel" and routes taps through your ViewModel.
- **`OnNavigating` + `GetDeferral()`** — catches swipe-back and hardware back; `GetDeferral()` is required because `DisplayAlert` is async. Without it the navigation completes before the dialog returns.
- **`args.Cancel()`** — stops the navigation so the user stays on the page.
